{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17631075","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17631075"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:22:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:22:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17345"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17345","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17345"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.51,0.02,0.46,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10035"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112967"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10035","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10035"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17345"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94999"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6911"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23494"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23499"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112967","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112967"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe duodenum receives its arterial blood supply from vessels that form important anastomoses between two major arterial systems.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the arterial supply to the duodenum?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Branches from the gastroduodenal and splenic arteries","Branches from the right and left gastric arteries","Superior and inferior pancreaticoduodenal arteries forming anastomotic arcades","Branches from the right and left gastroepiploic arteries","Branches from the dorsal and greater pancreatic arteries"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe duodenum receives its blood supply from the \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperior and inferior pancreaticoduodenal arteries forming anastomotic arcades\u003C/strong\u003E. The superior pancreaticoduodenal artery arises from the gastroduodenal artery (a branch of the common hepatic artery), while the inferior pancreaticoduodenal artery originates from the superior mesenteric artery. These vessels form anterior and posterior arcades that supply both the duodenum and head of the pancreas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBranches from the gastroduodenal and splenic arteries\u003C/strong\u003E - While the gastroduodenal artery contributes via the superior pancreaticoduodenal artery, the splenic artery does not supply the duodenum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBranches from the right and left gastric arteries\u003C/strong\u003E - These arteries supply the stomach, not the duodenum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBranches from the right and left gastroepiploic arteries\u003C/strong\u003E - These arteries supply the greater curvature of the stomach.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBranches from the dorsal and greater pancreatic arteries\u003C/strong\u003E - The dorsal pancreatic artery supplies the entire pancreas via arterial arcades. The greater pancreatic arteries supply the pancreatic body and tail.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The superior pancreaticoduodenal artery arises from the gastroduodenal artery and supplies the proximal duodenum.","The inferior pancreaticoduodenal artery arises from the superior mesenteric artery and supplies the distal duodenum.","The pancreaticoduodenal arteries form anterior and posterior arcades that supply both the duodenum and pancreatic head."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94999"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17345"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94999","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94999"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-08T17:21:03+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-08T17:21:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10035"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112967"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4926"},"attrib